<div id="review_2361013254" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2361013254" />
    <a title="Ms." class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/43170162-ms"><img alt="Ms." src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1599319601p2/43170162.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2361013254?book_show_action=true">Apr 14, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ms." class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ms." href="/user/show/43170162-ms">Ms.</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2361013254" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11777316686726695719">3.5/5 stars<br/><br/>I came to learn about <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/159178.North_and_South__North_and_South___1_' title='North and South (North and South, #1) by John Jakes' rel='nofollow noopener'>North and South</a> from watching the 1980&apos;s miniseries adapted from the novels. I read the first book in the trilogy about a year ago, and thoroughly enjoyed it for the melodramatic yet riveting soap opera that it was. I loved the concept: two boys - Orry Main from South Carolina, and George Hazard from Pennsylvania - meet at West Point Academy and become best friends. Through their friendship, a bond is formed between their two families that must withstand the stra</span>
  <span id="freeText11777316686726695719" style="display:none">3.5/5 stars<br /><br />I came to learn about <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/159178.North_and_South__North_and_South___1_" title="North and South (North and South, #1) by John Jakes" rel="nofollow noopener">North and South</a> from watching the 1980's miniseries adapted from the novels. I read the first book in the trilogy about a year ago, and thoroughly enjoyed it for the melodramatic yet riveting soap opera that it was. I loved the concept: two boys - Orry Main from South Carolina, and George Hazard from Pennsylvania - meet at West Point Academy and become best friends. Through their friendship, a bond is formed between their two families that must withstand the strain of the events of the Civil War. <br /><br />There are a LOT of characters in this series. and a LOT of different perspectives. The story is complex and painstakingly researched. I love sweeping, epic stories with many characters and subplots, but I can see how that would not be everyone's cup of tea. <br /><br />I can also see why a lot of reviewers said they couldn't finish this second installment in the series. The first half of it was onerous. Boring, dense, slow-paced. And this book is over 1,000 pages long! So that's over 500 pages that ramble on and on about how Senator Whatshisface passed such-and-such a bill while General Whocares got a promotion and Brigadier Irrelevant gave a speech and blah blah blah blah. The main characters - the ones we grew to know and love in the first book - become secondary to the historical backdrop. <br /><br />The second half of this book though...had me shook. Jakes writes action scenes so well, and is fantastic at building suspense during these sequences. He is also great at melodrama in general. Yes, it's corny. Yes, people fall in love way too quickly and the antagonists are all really ridiculous and over-the-top but I'm here for it. It makes for a great story. Once you get past the first 500 pages, of course. <br /><br />I am hoping this is just a case of Middle Book Syndrome, and that <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/64279.Heaven_and_Hell__North_and_South___3_" title="Heaven and Hell (North and South, #3) by John Jakes" rel="nofollow noopener">Heaven and Hell</a> will be better than this one. Or at least more consistent. It will be a while before I pick that up, though. My brain is tuckered out from this brick of a book. </span>
  <a data-text-id="11777316686726695719" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


