  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2488499326" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2488499326" />
    <a title="Stephanie" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/55458034-stephanie"><img alt="Stephanie" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1505362158p2/55458034.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2488499326?book_show_action=true">Nov 10, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Stephanie" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Stephanie" href="/user/show/55458034-stephanie">Stephanie</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2488499326" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10246786035761465978">I&apos;d give this book 4 stars for the detail, research, and effort the author put into it. Maybe even 5. But it&apos;s getting 3 for the actual enjoyment I derived from reading it. <br/><br/>Which isn&apos;t the book&apos;s fault; historical fiction isn&apos;t one of my go-to genres. I can&apos;t even remember how I heard about this series or why I wanted to read it. I was probably just trying something new. Good for me.<br/><br/>And I do like certain aspects of it; I like that it&apos;s basically a big, grand Civil War era soap opera in book form</span>
  <span id="freeText10246786035761465978" style="display:none">I'd give this book 4 stars for the detail, research, and effort the author put into it. Maybe even 5. But it's getting 3 for the actual enjoyment I derived from reading it. <br /><br />Which isn't the book's fault; historical fiction isn't one of my go-to genres. I can't even remember how I heard about this series or why I wanted to read it. I was probably just trying something new. Good for me.<br /><br />And I do like certain aspects of it; I like that it's basically a big, grand Civil War era soap opera in book form. But after awhile....I just get bored, people. I want to read other things. This book is over 1000 pages long, and there are two other equally lengthy books in this series. And there are so many characters to keep track of. Ridiculously minor characters get brought back for about a paragraph of story focused on them and all you're doing the whole time is trying to remember who they are. Then by the time you do, they disappear for 500 pages and you end up repeating the whole process when they randomly pop back up again.<br /><br />The main characters aren't all that great either. They're the kind of characters who have one characteristic you're given to focus on: Orry's is that he has one arm. Charles is sullen. Constance is plump. Madeline is of mixed race. Cooper....Cooper needs to figure his shit out, man. He was the only character I really liked in the first book because he was the only character who was really passionate about anything. But he turns into a grade A asshole for most of this one, and I'm pretty sure that trend is going to continue into the final book.<br /><br />It's also kind of awkward liking any of the characters anyway; they're all, at the very least, 10% racist. And I get that it's set during a time where pretty much everyone was racist, and to their credit, several of the characters get much better about it as the series goes on. But it's still awkward.<br /><br />However, although I very much enjoy mentioning things I didn't like about this book (I was stuck with it for 1000+ pages, I think I've earned that much!) I'll certainly give it this: Love and War is very good at being what it is -- a big historical fiction novel set in the Civil War era. It's not exactly to my tastes, but is it still a good novel? Yes, I would say so.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10246786035761465978" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

